title: For Sale:  Enfield No. 1 Mk 3 SHTLE Made in 1917 all matching with bayonet
postcontent:
This is a really nice Enfield No. 1 Mk III, made in England at the original Enfield factory ("Enfield" stamp on rear band, see picture 3). The working parts are all matching. The only exceptions are the nose cap and the stock, which are original replacements. This is NOT a drill rifle- the original stock split, which is why I had to put it in a new stock. Can be cleaned up with a little Jasco and steam, the paint will come right off. The original stock is included, along with a period-correct bayonet. The bayonet is English, stamped "1907" and then re-stamped "1917" over it. Bayonet has the crown stamp. The dark spots on the blade are just grease, not rust. Can take more pictures to prove it, or you could see it in person if you're seriously interested. As for the rifle, it's great. The crown, I'd rate an 8/10. The bore is dark, but with strong rifling. Great shooter. The magazine appears to be original. The gun still has about (in my non-professional opinion) 80% of the original bluing remaining. It's very rare to find a rifle like this in such good condition, especially with the parts all matching. I had this rifle appraised by a collector, and he valued it at around 450 without the bayonet. I'm including the bayonet, worth around 100 dollars, for free. All trades entertained, but I'd prefer anything military surplus, plus cash if necessary. Cash is king, etc. Thanks for looking! title: For Sale:  Colt Junior  Auto pistol in .25 ACP
postcontent: This is a Colt Junior  Automatic pistol in .25ACP. It is in very good condition with great bluing all around, except for a wear point on each side of the very front of the slide. This was made in the USA by Colt in the earlier 1970's, and not made in Spain (by Astra)  as some earlier types were prior to the Gun Control Act  of 1968.  Those made in Spain are so stamped on the right hand side behind the trigger.  Pistol has one magazine, and fires in single action only. The wood grips or panels are in  great condition with no damage or defects, with the Colt medallion.  This is about the smallest auto pistol out there, smaller even the the KelTec P32, although it is heavier than that model, with it's all steel construction versus polymer commonly seen today. This weighs 12.6 ounces with an empty magazine inserted. A rarely seen firearm, and a Colt as well.

title: For Sale:  Match grade .300 winmag tactical/hunting rifle with Nightforce optic
postcontent:
Only fired 20 times, match grade custom rifle chambered in .300 win mag, built by Red Hawk Rifles out in Grand Junction CO. It is the very rifle featured on their front page at redhawkrifles.com (although now it has the non-adjustable Bell and Carlson 700LA A2 stock as opposed to the A5 adjustable to save weight, and will be sold with the A2 stock as shown in the pictures with it inside the case). Their custom rifles are renowned for their accuracy, and this weapons system is capable of reliably hitting targets up to 1200 meters, making it a top choice for any precision hunting/tactical engagement. 

*Please note you can see more pictures via this downloadable zip file: http://cameronmacpherson.com/rifle-pics.zip

It was custom built upon a Remington 700 action, it has a heavy fluted tactical barrel threaded with a muzzle brake, a spiral fluted bolt, and a tactical bolt handle with a teardrop knob. The actual bolt and internal working mechanisms have been custom calibrated for maximum accuracy by the RHR gunsmiths. I have only fired the rifle 20 times in total when sighting in an old optic I have since replaced. The currently included optic is a mounted Nightforce NXS 5.5-20x56mm Mil Dot Optic with Zero Stop, brand new, I haven't even had a chance to sight it in.

In addition to the rifle, it comes with the following:

* New Nightforce NXS 5.5-20x56mm Mil Dot Optic with Zero Stop (mounted, unsighted)
* Pelican hardbody wheeled case pre cut out
* 2 5rd magazines
* 2 10rd magazines
* Harris tactical bipod
* Bell and Carlson 700 LA A2 tactical stock
* 38 rd rocky mountain custom match grade rounds with nosler bullets ($3-4 per rd)
* 20 rd box Fiocchi high grade ammunition
* 20 rd box standard grade Remington ammunition.  
* 1 .300 win mag laser boresighter. 

I'm terribly sorry to see this go, it is a work of beauty and one of my favorite rifles, but the realities of this economy are coming face to face with the fact that I never have a chance to actually use it. I'm hoping will go to a good home with someone who will be able to enjoy it more frequently. 

Please let me know if you have any questions or would like to make a reasonable offer. I would greatly prefer to deal within Colorado, but I will ship to an FFL of your choice if need be.

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Civil War Burnside Carbine
postcontent: This is a 5th Model 1863-64 Burnside Carbine in .54 cal percussion. About identical to the fourth model but very noticeable guide screw in the center of the right frame that allows smoother operation of the breech as it rides in the corresponding curved groove in the breech block. Widely used during the Civil War, this carbine was issued to Union Cavalry regiments of the 1st Michigan; 3rd Indiana; 5th, 6th, & 7th Ohio; 1st NJ; 3rd WV; 3rd, 14th, & 18th PA; and 2nd, 12th, 14th & 16th Illinois. Matching SN 15745 on frame and breech block. 21" round .54 cal. barrel. Still readable “BURNSIDE RIFLE Co/PROVIDENCE R.I.” on the lockplate. Front blade sight and folding rear sight. Saddle bar and ring on left side. Action tight and functions smoothly; good shootable bore with rifling. Metal surfaces blued, turned to a scattered patina. Oil finished walnut stock showing numerous light blemishes and handling marks. There are signs of inspector’s cartouche on left side, but unreadable. This popular and highly collectable carbine is being sold from a Civil War collection.
